## Setup

### Prerequisites

- Python 3.10+
- Access to a [vLLM](https://github.com/vllm-project/vllm) inference endpoint serving `Llama-OpenReviewer-8B`
- An Anthropic API key

### Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/TimVSu/Llama-Openreviewer-Paraphrasing-Attack
cd TimVSu/Llama-Openreviewer-Paraphrasing-Attack
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### Configuration

Copy `.env.example` to `.env.local` and fill in the values:

```env
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=           # Anthropic API key for paraphrase generation
TIMEOUT=300.0                # HTTP timeout in seconds
SEMANTIC_THRESHOLD=0.8       # Minimum cosine similarity for a valid paraphrase (0–1)
WORD_THRESHOLD=3             # Minimum word-level edit distance for a valid paraphrase

PAPER_PATH=                  # Path to the input paper in Markdown format
PARAPHRASING_PROMPT_PATH=    # Path to the system prompt used for paraphrase generation
REVIEW_PROMPT_PATH=          # Path to the system prompt for the review pass
RATING_PROMPT_PATH=          # Path to the system prompt for the rating pass

INFERENCE_ENDPOINT_URL=      # Base URL of the vLLM endpoint
INFERENCE_TOKEN=             # Bearer token for the vLLM endpoint if necessary
INFERENCE_ENDPOINT_MODEL=    # Model path for the vLLM endpoint e.g. /repository on Huggingface endpoints

PARAPHRASES_DIR=             # Directory to cache generated paraphrases (.tsv)
RESULTS_PATH=                # Output path for the optimized paper (.md)
SCORES_PATH=                 # Path to the scores log (.csv)
CHECKPOINT_DIR=              # Directory for optimization checkpoints
```

---

## Usage

```bash
python3 root.py
```

Or to keep the logs

```bash
python -u root.py >> ../logs/<logs_file>
```

On first run, paraphrases are generated and saved to `PARAPHRASES_DIR`. You will be prompted before the optimization begins, allowing you to inspect the paraphrases first. Subsequent runs with the same paper and settings will load cached paraphrases automatically.

If a run is interrupted, it will resume from the last checkpoint automatically.

---

## Project Structure

```
.
├── root.py                  # Entry point and optimization loop
├── utils.py                 # Sentence extraction, paraphrasing, scoring, I/O utilities
├── prompts/
│   ├── paraphrasing.md      # System prompt for paraphrase generation
│   ├── review.md            # System prompt for the review pass
│   └── rating.md            # System prompt for the rating pass
├── paraphrases/             # Cached paraphrase TSV files (PARAPHRASES_DIR)
├── checkpoints/             # Run checkpoints (CHECKPOINT_DIR)
└── .env.local               # Local environment configuration
```

---

## Key Parameters

| Parameter | Description | Default |
|---|---|---|
| `SEMANTIC_THRESHOLD` | Cosine similarity threshold for paraphrase validity | `0.8` |
| `WORD_THRESHOLD` | Minimum word edit distance between original and paraphrase | `3` |
| `TIMEOUT` | HTTP request timeout in seconds | `300.0` |

---

## Output

- **Optimized paper** — Written to `RESULTS_PATH` in Markdown format.
- **Scores log** — A CSV appended to `SCORES_PATH` with columns: `paper`, `paraphrases`, `original_score`, `improved_score`.

---

## Notes

- The paraphrase cache filename encodes the paper name, semantic threshold, and word threshold (e.g., `paper_paraphrases_80_3.tsv`), so changing these parameters will trigger a fresh paraphrase generation run.
- The create_endpoint file serves as an example for a working modal endpoint. Other providers are possible but the endpoint has to use vLLM.
- Up to 5 sentence evaluations are run concurrently per iteration via an async semaphore.
- convert_to_md.py can be used to convert papers in JSON format from the peerRead Github to markdown.
- create_plots.py extracts relevant information from log files and uses it to create line plots.